---
import Dossier from '../../../layouts/Dossier.astro';
import Annot from '../../../components/Annot.astro';
import AnnotLine from '../../../components/AnnotLine.astro';
import ClaimRef from '../../../components/ClaimRef.astro';
import CId from '../../../components/CId.astro';
import { getClaim } from '../../../lib/data';
import { rangeAbbrev } from '../../../lib/format';

const range = rangeAbbrev(getClaim('C-0024')); // $18–24 bn (Tier 4, ranges only)
---

<Dossier slug="projection" cites={['C-0024', 'C-0027', 'C-0011', 'C-0019']}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="label" style="margin-bottom:12px">CIA · FY2025 · MODELED RANGE:</div>
    <div class="figure">{range}</div>
    <Annot>
      <AnnotLine>An estimate, not a fact: the Central Intelligence Agency's likely budget today, shown as a range because the real number is secret.</AnnotLine>
      <ClaimRef id="C-0024" />
      <AnnotLine>Tier 4: an estimate. Shown as a range, never a single number, and never added to official figures.</AnnotLine>
      <AnnotLine key="Assumptions">FY2013 share 28% · drift band ±1.25%/yr compounded</AnnotLine>
      <AnnotLine key="Sanity check">intelligence ≈ 11% of national defense (<CId id="C-0027" />)</AnnotLine>
      <AnnotLine key="Method">METHODOLOGY 4.1 · ratio persistence</AnnotLine>
    </Annot>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="stack">
      <p class="body">This figure is an estimate — the only modeled number shown in this edition, and the only figure here that is not drawn directly from an official or authenticated record. It carries a range, a published assumption list, and a Tier 4 label, and it is never added to anything else.</p>
      <p class="body">The method is ratio persistence (METHODOLOGY 4.1): the Central Intelligence Agency's 28% share of the leaked fiscal year 2013 request (C-0019) is carried forward onto the appropriated fiscal year 2025 National Intelligence Program of $73.3 billion (C-0011), producing a central value near $20.5 billion. A drift band of ±1.25% per year, compounded across twelve years of unknown reallocation, widens that to the $18–24 billion range shown (C-0024).</p>
      <p class="body">As a check, the result is compared against the Congressional Research Service finding that intelligence spending has held near 11% of national defense spending since 2007 (C-0027). The two approaches agree to within the band. That agreement is a reason to state a range; it is not a reason to state a point.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Dossier>
